`IFormFile` buffers the entire request body into memory by default. For large files, read the raw body stream directly:

```csharp
// Program.cs
app.MapPost("/upload", async (HttpRequest request) =>
{
    // Disable the default form body size limit
    if (!request.HasFormContentType)
        return Results.BadRequest("Expected multipart/form-data");

    var boundary = request.GetMultipartBoundary();
    if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(boundary))
        return Results.BadRequest("Missing boundary");

    var reader = new Microsoft.AspNetCore.WebUtilities.MultipartReader(boundary, request.Body);
    var section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();

    while (section is not null)
    {
        if (ContentDispositionHeaderValue.TryParse(section.ContentDisposition, out var cd)
            && cd.IsFileDisposition())
        {
            var fileName = Path.GetRandomFileName(); // sanitize!
            var savePath = Path.Combine("/data/uploads", fileName);

            await using var fs = File.Create(savePath);
            await section.Body.CopyToAsync(fs);   // streams chunk-by-chunk
        }
        section = await reader.ReadNextSectionAsync();
    }

    return Results.Ok("Uploaded");
})
.DisableAntiforgery();
```

**Key configuration to raise the limits:**

```csharp
// Program.cs — before Build()
builder.WebHost.ConfigureKestrel(opts =>
{
    opts.Limits.MaxRequestBodySize = 2L * 1024 * 1024 * 1024; // 2 GB
});

// Disable form value/multipart body length limits for this endpoint
app.MapPost("/upload", handler)
   .WithMetadata(new Microsoft.AspNetCore.Http.Features.FormOptions
   {
       MultipartBodyLengthLimit = long.MaxValue
   });
```

**Why this works:**

| Approach | Memory use | Mechanism |
|----------|-----------|-----------|
| `IFormFile` | Entire file in RAM | Buffered model binding |
| `MultipartReader` | ~80 KB buffer | Reads stream section-by-section |

**Checklist:**

1. **Don't bind `IFormFile`** — bypass model binding entirely.  
2. **Set `MaxRequestBodySize`** on Kestrel (default is ~28 MB).  
3. **Use `MultipartReader`** to iterate sections and `CopyToAsync` to disk.  
4. If behind IIS/Nginx, also raise `maxAllowedContentLength` / `client_max_body_size`.  
5. Consider writing to a temp file first, then moving atomically to the final path.
